#X text 743 186 As show before \, a proper Tremolo is an LFO with a depth control. It's worth noting how the tremolo effect can also be applied to any sound input \, like a guitar or whatever., f 45;
#X floatatom 716 363 5 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X obj 716 389 bpm2hz 1/16;
#X obj 716 336 initmess 75;
#X obj 627 440 tremolo~, f 26;
#X text 843 290 You can set your tremolo effect according to a BPM value with [bpm2hz] \, so it is synced to a beat., f 25;
#X obj 806 363 initmess 0.75;
#X text 57 39 This example focuses on 'slow' amplitude modulations. A period one with a low frequency give us a tremolo effect \, which is something we've already seen and will revisit in this section. But first \, let's start by emphasizing how envelopes are also 'slow' modulators or controllers of the amplitude that greatly shape the chacteristics of a sound and are efficient and interesting sound design tools. Below we revisit an old example of a percussive decay envelope, f 68;
#X obj 593 178 voices~ 4;
#X obj 593 212 mtof~;
#X text 685 32 And now let's try a polyphonic patch via multichannel connections., f 35;
#X obj 616 302 moog~ 2500 0.25 0.25;
#X obj 628 353 vca~;
#X text 760 472 This polyphonic patch works because the oscillator \, the envelop and filter objects can deal with Multi Channel connections. Actually \, so does [tremolo~] \, but we don't need to process different channels in it. The [vca~] object also sums the channel into a single output. Using the VCA after the filter is good because [moog~] can self oscillate. Also \, filtering the channels separately produces a different character., f 51;
